@@ -0,0 +1,98 @@
+# Voice
+
+`ollama voice` lets you talk to a model with your voice and hear its replies. The
+entire speech pipeline runs locally on the CPU — no GPU and no cloud required:
+
+- **VAD** — Silero voice-activity detection captures one spoken turn from your mic
+- **STT** — Parakeet (ONNX) transcribes speech to text, served on `:5093`
+- **LLM** — your transcript is sent to a model through the normal Ollama chat API
+- **TTS** — Supertonic (ONNX) speaks the reply, served on `:8766`
+
+Ollama only orchestrates the `listen → chat → speak` loop; the STT/TTS backends are
+small local HTTP servers installed on first use.
+
+## Install the speech backends
+
+The speech models and their Python backends are installed once with:
+
+```shell
+ollama voice --setup
+```
+
+`--setup` is an **interactive installer**. It detects your OS/GPU, proposes an
+acceleration backend, and lets you choose. It creates `~/.ollama/voice/` (override with
+`OLLAMA_VOICE_HOME`), installs the VAD venv, clones and starts the Parakeet STT and
+Supertonic TTS servers, and registers auto-start units (systemd `--user` on Linux,
+launchd on macOS, Task Scheduler on Windows) so they survive reboots.
+
+### Acceleration
+
+| `--accel` | Where | What it installs |
+| --- | --- | --- |
+| `auto` (default) | any | macOS → `coreml`, Linux+NVIDIA → `cuda`, otherwise `cpu` |
+| `cpu` | any | plain `onnxruntime` — portable, already fast (Parakeet ~9–21×, Supertonic ~3–12× realtime) |
+| `cuda` | Linux | `onnxruntime-gpu` on an NVIDIA GPU |
+| `coreml` | macOS | Apple Neural Engine — **Supertonic-3 CoreML** (`CPU_AND_NE`), mirroring the project's reference Mac config |
+| `directml` | Windows | `onnxruntime-directml` for GPU |
+
+Run it non-interactively with the auto-detected default using `--yes`, or force a path:
+
+```shell
+ollama voice --setup --accel cpu --yes      # scriptable, no prompt
+ollama voice --setup --accel coreml         # macOS Neural Engine
+```
+
+The installer records your choice and the resolved backend URLs in
+`~/.ollama/voice/voice.env`, which the voice command reads at runtime.
+
+Requirements: `python` (3.10+, 3.11 for the macOS CoreML backend) and `git` on `PATH`
+(plus `git-lfs` for the CoreML model weights). Audio playback uses the system player
+(`afplay` on macOS; `ffplay`/`aplay`/`paplay` on Linux; the built-in player on Windows).
+Linux, macOS, and Windows are all supported.
+
+## Talk to a model
+
+```shell
+ollama voice llama3.2
+```
+
+Speak after the tone. Your transcript is shown with `>>>`, the model's reply is printed
+and spoken, then it listens again. Press `Ctrl-C` to exit.
+
+Flags:
+
+| Flag | Description |
+| --- | --- |
+| `--setup` | Install and start the local STT/TTS backends (interactive) |
+| `--accel auto\|cpu\|cuda\|coreml` | Acceleration for `--setup` (default: auto) |
+| `--yes` | Non-interactive `--setup`: accept the auto-detected acceleration |
+| `--lang en\|es` | Spoken-language hint (default: auto-detect) |
+| `--no-speak` | Transcribe and chat without speaking replies aloud |
+| `--keepalive 5m` | How long to keep the model loaded |
+| `--think` | Enable thinking mode for supported models |
+
+## Inside `ollama run`
+
+You can also flip an existing chat session into voice with a slash command:
+
+```
+>>> /voice         # start talking; speak after the tone
+>>> /voice off     # back to the keyboard
+```
+
+`Ctrl-C` while in voice mode also returns you to typing.
+
+## Configuration
+
+The backends are plain HTTP services, so you can point Ollama at remote or alternative
+ones with environment variables:
+
+| Variable | Default | Description |
+| --- | --- | --- |
+| `OLLAMA_VOICE_HOME` | `~/.ollama/voice` | Install/runtime directory |
+| `STT_URL` | `http://127.0.0.1:5093/v1/audio/transcriptions` | Speech-to-text endpoint |
+| `SUPERTONIC_URL` | `http://127.0.0.1:8766` | Text-to-speech endpoint |
+| `TTS_ENGINE` | `supertonic` | TTS engine (`supertonic`, `neutts`, `xai`) |
+| `VAD_THRESHOLD` | `0.5` | Mic speech-detection sensitivity |
+| `TALK_IDLE_TIMEOUT_S` | `30` | Stop listening after N seconds of silence |
+| `MIC_QUERY` | _(auto)_ | Substring to pick a specific microphone |
